## 1. Introduction & Theory

### 1.1 What is GitLab CI/CD?

**GitLab CI/CD** is the built-in continuous integration and delivery system of **GitLab**, a complete DevOps platform. It automates building, testing, and deploying code through pipelines defined in a single YAML file — **`.gitlab-ci.yml`** — stored in your repository. Because GitLab unifies source control, CI/CD, container registry, security scanning, and issue tracking in one application, it's often described as a "single application for the entire DevOps lifecycle."

### 1.2 Why GitLab CI/CD?

| Feature | Explanation |
|---------|-------------|
| **All-in-one** | SCM + CI/CD + registry + security + monitoring in one platform |
| **Pipeline-as-code** | `.gitlab-ci.yml` versioned with the code |
| **Runners** | Flexible execution: shared, group, or self-hosted, on any OS/container |
| **Auto DevOps** | Opinionated, zero-config pipelines |
| **Built-in security** | SAST, DAST, dependency & container scanning out of the box |
| **Self-hostable** | Run your own GitLab instance or use GitLab.com SaaS |
| **Environments & reviews** | Built-in deploy environments and review apps |

### 1.3 How it works

```
   Commit / MR / schedule
        │ triggers
        ▼
   Pipeline  (.gitlab-ci.yml)
        │ organized into ordered
        ▼
   Stages  (build → test → deploy)   [run sequentially]
        │ each stage contains
        ▼
   Jobs   [run in parallel within a stage]
        │ executed by a
        ▼
   Runner  (shell, Docker, Kubernetes executor)
```

- **Pipeline:** The top-level CI/CD process, triggered by events.
- **Stage:** A phase of the pipeline (e.g., `build`, `test`, `deploy`). Stages run **in order**.
- **Job:** A unit of work in a stage. Jobs in the **same stage run in parallel**.
- **Runner:** An agent that executes jobs. GitLab.com provides shared runners; you can register your own.
- **Executor:** How a runner runs jobs — Shell, Docker, Docker Machine, or Kubernetes.

### 1.4 Architecture

```
   GitLab Server (gitlab.com or self-hosted)
        │ assigns jobs
        ▼
   +------------------+   +------------------+   +------------------+
   | Shared Runner    |   | Group Runner     |   | Self-hosted      |
   | (Docker executor)|   | (K8s executor)   |   | (Shell executor) |
   +------------------+   +------------------+   +------------------+
        │ pulls job, runs script, reports status + artifacts back
        ▼
   Artifacts, container images (registry), environments, security reports
```

### 1.5 When to use GitLab CI/CD

- Teams already on GitLab (SaaS or self-managed).
- Wanting an integrated DevOps platform (less tool sprawl).
- Needing self-hosted/on-prem CI with strong security scanning.
- GitOps and Kubernetes deployments (GitLab Agent for Kubernetes).

When **not** ideal: code hosted on GitHub (use GitHub Actions), or very lightweight needs where a hosted SaaS CI is simpler.

