## 3. Core Concepts

### 3.1 BEGINNER

#### 3.1.1 Stages and jobs

```yaml
stages:            # defines order
  - build
  - test
  - deploy

compile:
  stage: build
  script: [ "make build" ]

unit-tests:
  stage: test
  script: [ "make test" ]

lint:
  stage: test          # runs in parallel with unit-tests
  script: [ "make lint" ]

deploy-prod:
  stage: deploy
  script: [ "./deploy.sh" ]
```

If a job fails, later stages don't run (by default).

#### 3.1.2 The script keyword

```yaml
job:
  before_script:
    - echo "setup"
  script:
    - echo "main commands"
    - npm ci
    - npm test
  after_script:
    - echo "cleanup (always runs)"
```

#### 3.1.3 Choosing an image

Each job can run in a specific Docker image (with the Docker executor):

```yaml
test:
  image: node:20-alpine
  script:
    - node --version
    - npm ci && npm test
```

#### 3.1.4 Variables

```yaml
variables:
  APP_ENV: production       # pipeline-level

job:
  variables:
    JOB_VAR: value          # job-level
  script:
    - echo "$APP_ENV - $JOB_VAR"
    - echo "Branch: $CI_COMMIT_REF_NAME"
    - echo "Commit: $CI_COMMIT_SHA"
```

GitLab provides many **predefined variables** (`CI_COMMIT_SHA`, `CI_PIPELINE_ID`, `CI_PROJECT_DIR`, `CI_REGISTRY`, etc.).

#### 3.1.5 Pipeline status

Pipelines show in the UI with stage/job graphs. Merge requests display pipeline status and can be set to require a green pipeline before merging.

### 3.2 INTERMEDIATE

#### 3.2.1 Artifacts

```yaml
build:
  stage: build
  script:
    - npm run build
  artifacts:
    paths:
      - dist/
    expire_in: 1 week
    reports:
      junit: test-results.xml    # special report types render in MR
```

Artifacts pass files to later stages and are downloadable from the UI.

#### 3.2.2 Caching

```yaml
cache:
  key: ${CI_COMMIT_REF_SLUG}     # per-branch cache
  paths:
    - node_modules/
    - .npm/

job:
  cache:
    key:
      files: [ package-lock.json ]
    paths: [ node_modules/ ]
```

> **Cache vs. artifacts:** cache speeds up builds (dependencies, not guaranteed to persist); artifacts are deliverables passed reliably between jobs.

#### 3.2.3 Rules and conditions

```yaml
deploy-prod:
  stage: deploy
  script: [ "./deploy.sh" ]
  rules:
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_BRANCH == "main"'
      when: manual                    # require a click to deploy
    - if: '$CI_COMMIT_TAG'
      when: on_success
    - when: never                     # otherwise don't run
```

`rules` (modern) replace the older `only`/`except`. Conditions can match branches, tags, MRs, variables, and changed files (`changes:`).

#### 3.2.4 `needs` (DAG pipelines)

```yaml
build-a:
  stage: build
  script: [ "make a" ]

test-a:
  stage: test
  needs: [ build-a ]      # start as soon as build-a finishes, not whole stage
  script: [ "make test-a" ]
```

`needs` creates a **directed acyclic graph**, letting jobs start early instead of waiting for an entire stage — faster pipelines.

#### 3.2.5 Environments and deployments

```yaml
deploy-staging:
  stage: deploy
  script: [ "./deploy.sh staging" ]
  environment:
    name: staging
    url: https://staging.example.com

deploy-prod:
  stage: deploy
  script: [ "./deploy.sh production" ]
  environment:
    name: production
    url: https://example.com
  when: manual
```

Environments track deployments, enable rollback, and power **review apps** (ephemeral environments per merge request).

#### 3.2.6 CI/CD variables and secrets

Define under **Settings → CI/CD → Variables**:
- **Protected** — only available on protected branches/tags.
- **Masked** — hidden in job logs.
- **File** type — written to a temp file (for certs/keys).

```yaml
deploy:
  script:
    - echo "$DEPLOY_TOKEN" | docker login -u ci --password-stdin
```

#### 3.2.7 Services

```yaml
test:
  image: python:3.12
  services:
    - postgres:16
  variables:
    POSTGRES_PASSWORD: pass
    DATABASE_URL: "postgres://postgres:pass@postgres:5432/test"
  script:
    - pytest
```

Service containers (databases, redis) run alongside the job and are reachable by service name.

### 3.3 ADVANCED

#### 3.3.1 Templates: extends, include, anchors

```yaml
# Reuse with extends
.base-test:
  image: node:20
  before_script: [ "npm ci" ]

unit:
  extends: .base-test
  script: [ "npm run test:unit" ]

# Include external/templated config
include:
  - local: '/templates/security.yml'
  - project: 'my-group/ci-templates'
    file: '/build.yml'
    ref: main
  - template: 'Jobs/SAST.gitlab-ci.yml'   # built-in template
```

#### 3.3.2 Parent-child and multi-project pipelines

```yaml
# Trigger a child pipeline
child:
  trigger:
    include: child-pipeline.yml

# Trigger another project's pipeline
deploy-downstream:
  trigger:
    project: my-group/deploy-repo
    branch: main
```

Useful for monorepos (run only affected sub-pipelines) and cross-project orchestration.

#### 3.3.3 Dynamic pipelines

Generate `.gitlab-ci.yml` at runtime, then run it:

```yaml
generate:
  stage: build
  script: [ "./generate-ci.sh > generated.yml" ]
  artifacts:
    paths: [ generated.yml ]

run-generated:
  stage: test
  trigger:
    include:
      - artifact: generated.yml
        job: generate
```

#### 3.3.4 Built-in security scanning

```yaml
include:
  - template: Jobs/SAST.gitlab-ci.yml
  - template: Jobs/Dependency-Scanning.gitlab-ci.yml
  - template: Jobs/Container-Scanning.gitlab-ci.yml
  - template: Jobs/Secret-Detection.gitlab-ci.yml
```

Results appear in the **MR security widget** and **Vulnerability Report**. GitLab offers SAST, DAST, dependency scanning, container scanning, secret detection, and license compliance.

#### 3.3.5 Auto DevOps

GitLab's **Auto DevOps** provides an opinionated, zero-config pipeline that auto-detects your language, builds a container, runs tests/security scans, and deploys to Kubernetes — enabled in Settings with no `.gitlab-ci.yml` required. Good for getting started; customize as you mature.

#### 3.3.6 Kubernetes integration and GitOps

- **GitLab Agent for Kubernetes** establishes a secure connection for deployments and GitOps.
- Define environments backed by clusters; use review apps for per-MR previews.
- Combine with Helm/Kustomize for deployments.

#### 3.3.7 Runner executors and scaling

| Executor | Use |
|----------|-----|
| **Shell** | Run directly on the runner host (simple, less isolated) |
| **Docker** | Each job in a fresh container (common) |
| **Docker Machine / autoscale** | Spin up cloud VMs on demand |
| **Kubernetes** | Each job as a pod (elastic, cloud-native) |

```toml
# config.toml (Kubernetes executor)
[[runners]]
  executor = "kubernetes"
  [runners.kubernetes]
    namespace = "gitlab-runners"
    image = "alpine:latest"
```

#### 3.3.8 Merge trains and merged results pipelines

- **Merged results pipelines** run against the *result* of merging your MR into the target branch (catches integration issues).
- **Merge trains** queue MRs and validate them sequentially against each other to keep `main` always green at high throughput.

